{"type":"message","id":"ce2c121d","parentId":"66a1827e","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:43:35.395Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_3f01nbj5v2uq_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 123914\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine what single concrete action would best advance the goals.\r\n\r\nLooking at the current state:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are marked complete\r\n- CFI Analysis was just completed (2026-03-24)\r\n- Next pending actions include:\r\n  1. CFI-weighted compression experiment (compare next-pulse prediction vs frequency baseline)\r\n  2. Implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n  3. Distinguish \"constant format\" (freq=60, CFI=1) from \"research trajectory\" (freq<60, CFI>0.7)\r\n  4. Wire Breakaway pulses to real TemporalAttention backend\r\n  5. Design actual compression network\r\n\r\nThe most immediate and actionable next step based on the CFI findings would be the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would test the hypothesis that CFI weighting is better than frequency-only weighting for predicting next-pulse content.\r\n\r\nI need to look at the CFI_RESULTS.md to understand the data structure, then design and implement an experiment that compares:\r\n- Frequency-only baseline (current method)\r\n- CFI-weighted method (proposed improvement)\r\n\r\nLet me check what files exist and what data is available.\r\n\r\nActually, I should examine the existing state more carefully. The last pulse was pulse_2026-03-24 123815.md. Let me think about what concrete action I can take.\r\n\r\nGiven the CFI findings:\r\n- 44.8% of invariants have CFI=0 (pure noise/formatting)\r\n- 5.7% have CFI>=0.7 (true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181\r\n\r\nThe logical next step is to design a compression experiment that:\r\n1. Takes the existing invariant data\r\n2. Compares frequency-only compression vs CFI-weighted compression\r\n\r\n\r\n3. Measures which better predicts next-pulse content\r\n\r\nI'll focus on creating a structured experiment that quantifies the predictive power of CFI weighting. The goal is to develop a methodology that demonstrates the superiority of CFI-weighted compression in capturing meaningful content across pulses.\r\n\r\nI'll start by designing an experimental framework that can systematically compare compression approaches, focusing on measuring how well each method preserves critical information for predicting subsequent content.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\nLooking at the current state: CFI analysis is complete with key findings about 5.7% of invariants being true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7). The next logical step is to design and implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment to validate whether CFI weighting improves next-pulse prediction over frequency-only baseline.\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that ~45% of invariants are pure metaprogramming noise (CFI=0) while only ~6% are true causal anchors. We need to empirically test whether filtering/compressing based on CFI outperforms frequency-only methods.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate a new experiment script that compares frequency-only compression vs CFI-weighted compression on predicting next-pulse content, using the existing invariant data.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n**Date:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Goal:** Compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency-only baseline for next-pulse prediction\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression should outperform frequency-only because:\r\n1. Filters out 44.8% noise (CFI=0 metaprogramming artifacts)\r\n2. Prioritizes 5.7% true causal anchors (CFI≥0.7)\r\n3. Reduces semantic drift from formatting contamination\r\n\r\n## Methodology\r\n\r\n### Data Source\r\n- Use invariants from `research/INVARIANTS/` (session frequency data)\r\n- CFI values from `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n\r\n### Compression Methods to Compare\r\n\r\n| Method | Weight Formula | Description |\r\n|--------|---------------|-------------|\r\n| **Freq-Baseline** | w = freq | Current approach (normalized frequency) |\r\n| **CFI-Filter** | w = CFI × freq | CFI-weighted, includes all invariants |\r\n| **CFI-Threshold** | w = CFI × freq, CFI < 0.3 → 0 | Hard threshold at noise boundary |\r\n| **CFI-Strict** | w = CFI × freq, CFI < 0.7 → 0 | Only true causal anchors |\r\n\r\n### Evaluation Metric\r\n**Next-pulse content overlap**: For each pulse pair (P_n, P_{n+1}):\r\n1. Compress P_n using each method\r\n2. Measure token overlap with P_{n+1}\r\n3. Calculate precision/recall on preserved tokens\r\n\r\n### Expected Outcome\r\n- CFI-Threshold likely optimal: filters noise while retaining trajectory continuity\r\n- CFI-Strict may be too aggressive (misses some legitimate patterns)\r\n- If CFI methods don't improve, gap mechanism alone is sufficient\r\n\r\n## Implementation Steps\r\n1. [ ] Extract pulse text pairs from `pulse_*.md` files\r\n2. [ ] Map invariants to CFI values\r\n3. [ ] Implement four compression methods\r\n4. [ ] Run comparative evaluation\r\n5. [ ] Document results\r\n\r\n## Files Needed\r\n- `src/compression_experiment.py` - Main experiment script\r\n- `research/COMPRESSION_RESULTS.md` - Output documentation\r\nfile: research/COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT_DESIGN.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 12:39:41\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774370615392}}
